This is a spatial polygons dataset of the continental USA containing region and 2010/2015 population data. This is nice for someone who wants to the US sectioned off or want to see population trends by state from 2010 to 2015.

I initialized the package that contains this dataset.

#initialize spData package
library(spData)
## To access larger datasets in this package, install the spDataLarge
## package with: `install.packages('spDataLarge',
## repos='https://nowosad.github.io/drat/', type='source')`

I converted the data to spatial polygons

#read spatial polygons data for USA
library(sp)
library(sf)

I initialized leaflet and checked the polygons of the US to make sure it’s working

#initiate leaflet
library(leaflet)

#check polygons of USA
uspolygons %>%
  leaflet() %>%
  addPolygons() %>%
  addTiles()

I manually created categorical colors for the regions in the dataset. I tried to choose them to make them stand out from each other

#create categorical color variable for regions
uspolygons=as(us_states,Class = "Spatial")
regioncolor=c("blue","green","orange","red")
names(regioncolor)=c("Norteast","South","West","Midwest")
uspolygons$color=regioncolor[uspolygons$REGION]

Then, I plotted the categorical variable REGION here. Pretty straightforward.

#plot regions by color
uspolygons %>%
  leaflet() %>%
  addProviderTiles("Stamen") %>%
  addPolygons(
    color = ~color,
    label = ~paste0(NAME," ",REGION," ",total_pop_15),
    fillOpacity = .5
  )

I created numeric colors for US state population in 2010 using ggplot2.

#create numeric colors for USA state population in 2010
uspolygons=as(us_states,Class = "Spatial")
library(ggplot2)
usnumericcolor <- ggplot(uspolygons@data) +
  aes(
    x = NAME,
    y = total_pop_10,
    fill = total_pop_10,
    label = paste0(total_pop_10),
    total_pop_15=total_pop_15
  ) + 
  geom_col() + 
  geom_text(position = position_stack(0.5)) + 
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "darkred",mid = "orange",high = "darkgreen",midpoint = 50) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  coord_flip() + 
  labs(
    title = "US States Population 2010"
  )
usnumericcolor

Then, I merged those colors onto my spatial polygons so I could use plot it.

#merge color to spatial polygons dataset
uspolygons@data=merge(
  x=uspolygons@data,
  y=as.data.frame(ggplot_build(usnumericcolor)$data[[1]])[,c("total_pop_15","fill")],
  by="total_pop_15",
  all.x=TRUE,
  all.y=FALSE,
  sort=FALSE)

I plotted the colors using leaflet. As we can see, Texas and California dominate population-wise, with many of the eastern states holding down the middle and the rest of the country lagging behind. One might look at this and inform him or herself about the most popular states to live in, if they want to follow the crowd. They could also plan to go against the grain and live in the areas that are more sparse by going towards the middle or northwest of the country.

#plot numeric colors by USA state 2010 population
uspolygons %>%
  leaflet() %>%
  addProviderTiles("Stamen") %>%
  addPolygons(
    color = ~fill,
    label = ~paste0(NAME," ",REGION," ",total_pop_10),
    fillOpacity = .5)

We don’t really see much of a change in 5 years here. We can possibly infer that the US has a fairly stable population ratio among its states, and that the hypothetical person who wants to live somewhere can be assured that their preference of population density is met for a while.
